SvelteKit For-Each Loop

Table of Contents

  1. What is It?
  2. How to
  3. Results

What is It?

A For-Each loop is an iteration over a list of elements, where the program assigns the current element in the iteration to a variable name. The logistics of the loop are managed under-the-hood, so all you, the programmer, have to work with is the variables. This makes code appear more cleaner and readable. For-Each loops are most commonly used in front-end development when there are several cards which each contain different data to be read from objects. In this tutorial, we will use For-Each loops to iterate through objects that contain works from an art gallery.

How to

Within the Svelte language, there is a specific syntax made for this purpose. This syntax is not part of HTML nor JavaScript, but its own thing, to be substituted by the SvelteKit pre-processor. The syntax appears in this manner:

<h1>Gallery</h1>
<div class="gallery">
    {#each art as work}
        <a href="/Gallery/{work.id}">
            <figure>
                <img src="{`https://www.artic.edu/iiif/2/${work.image_id}/full/843,/0/default.jpg`}">
                <figcaption>
                    {work.artist_title}<br />
                    <span class="title">{work.title}</span> {work.date_display}<br />
                    {work.medium_display}
                </figcaption>
            </figure>
        </a>
    {/each}
</div>

As you can see in this example, art is the list to be iterated over while work is the makeshift name for the current element in the For-Each loop. In more formal terms, the syntax is defined as such:

{#each <list> as <element>}
    <!-- code goes here -->
{/each}

The first #each opens the loop while the last /each closes it. Only between these two eaches will the element variable be defined.
